{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ANnUioxF82yzsGvHZYXf3K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from recommendation results regardless of relevance score.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about filtering logic — does a function correctly exclude out-of-stock items? This could be a single module's filtering logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, subprocess needed. In-process fake catalog can test this.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the catalog would work fine here.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved — it's a filter rule.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\n\n- This is a pure filtering test at the unit level — given a list of products with stock status, the function should exclude out-of-stock ones.\n\n**Behavior 2: User preference filter correctly excludes blocked product categories.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Similar filtering logic based on user settings, testable at unit level.\n- REAL-INFRA: No external dependencies needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- The failure is in the filter logic itself, not module interaction.\n- This is also a unit-level test — the filter should correctly apply user preferences to exclude blocked categories.\n\n**Behavior 3: Recommendation algorithm ranks products matching user's recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: The ranking algorithm can be tested with fake input data.\n- REAL-INFRA: No.\n- LLM-DEP: The key question is whether the \"recommendation algorithm\" is a deterministic scoring function or an ML model. The description mentions weighing purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior — this sounds algorithmic rather than ML inference. I'm leaning toward Integration since it involves the ranking module processing multiple user data signals together, though if it's purely deterministic scoring logic it could be Unit.\n\nThe behavior itself is straightforward and verifiable: browsing signals should increase rank. That's a deterministic property I can test with known inputs. I'll classify this as **Integration** because the ranking algorithm likely needs to fetch browsing data from a data layer and combine it with product information, even though the core failure mode is algorithmic.\n\nMoving on to pagination — this tests whether the ordering remains stable across multiple requests for the same page. If the pagination logic is a pure function operating on fixed input, that's **Unit**. If it depends on data consistency guarantees, it becomes **Integration**. I'll go with **Unit** since deterministic sorting with in-memory data is straightforward to verify.\n\nNow looking at the next behavior about surfacing products from different categories...\n\nFor serendipity — the algorithm needs to verify it's recommending from categories the user hasn't explored. This is **Unit** territory since I can control the input (browsing history) and check the output includes unvisited categories.\n\nCold-start recommendations are trickier. The fallback logic itself could be **Unit**, but if it needs to fetch popularity data from a database, that pushes it to **Integration**. The distinction depends on whether popularity is mocked or queried from actual infrastructure.\n\nClick tracking needs to verify the data being persisted — product ID, position, and timestamp all recorded correctly. This could fail at the algorithm level or when writing to the tracking system.\n\nFor behavior 8, performance testing against a 100,000-product catalog requires real infrastructure and actual data volumes to measure meaningfully, so this needs to be a System-level test.\n\nNow looking at behavior 9 — after a purchase, the algorithm should deprioritize that product in future recommendations.  The algorithm needs to read from purchase history and apply the deprioritization rule, which means it's at least Integration-level since there's a data flow between purchase recording and the recommendation engine. It could theoretically be Unit if the algorithm is just a pure function receiving purchase history as input, but since the behavior describes \"subsequent requests,\" that implies state persistence, so Integration is the right minimum level.\n\nFor the determinism behavior, I'm thinking about whether the recommendation system uses ML or collaborative filtering. If it's ML-based, determinism with the same model weights should hold, but if it relies on LLM calls, that introduces non-determinism. The behavior is testing that identical user state produces identical recommendations, which is a Unit concern if the algorithm is deterministic, or an Agentic concern if LLMs are involved.\n\nSince the description doesn't mention LLMs explicitly, I'm treating this as an Integration test — the algorithm needs to consistently read user state and produce stable results. Now I'm going through each behavior and categorizing them: most of the filtering and ranking logic are Unit tests since they're pure functions, the cold-start fallback and click tracking are Integration tests because they depend on external data sources, the performance test is System-level, and the determinism check is Integration since it validates state consistency across calls. multiple calls with same state — the real question is whether we're testing with mocked state (Unit) or actual persistence across API calls (Integration). The phrasing \"requesting recommendations twice\" suggests full pipeline behavior, so I'll classify this as Integration to ensure state reading stays consistent. Now I'm settling on the final breakdown: filtering, preference logic, and ranking are Unit tests; cold-start fallback and click tracking need Integration; performance requires System testing. Now I'm writing out the test cases with their descriptions and assertions. For the unit tests, I'm covering the core filtering logic — availability filters removing out-of-stock items, preference filters blocking certain categories, ranking algorithms boosting products from browsing history, pagination consistency, and cross-category recommendations appearing in results.\n\nMoving into integration tests, I'm checking that new users with no history get ranked results based on popularity, click events are properly tracked with correct metadata, and purchase events influence future rankings by deprioritizing recently bought items. For the system test, I'm verifying the service handles a large product catalog within performance constraints, and I'm setting up a test that validates user state consistency across multiple recommendation calls.\n\nNow I'm assigning test classifications and probability distributions across the different test levels based on whether each test uses isolated in-memory data or requires external dependencies. Looking at the probability distributions for tests 9 and 10, which involve purchase history and multi-call state consistency. Now I'm reconsidering tests 3 and 5 — the recommendation algorithm could be ML-based, which would push them toward Agentic classification, but the specific behaviors being tested (browsing signals affecting rank, serendipity injection) sound more deterministic and rule-based, so I'll keep Unit as primary while giving Agentic some probability weight.\n\nFor test 6, I'm realizing the real concern is the cold-start fallback logic and whether it properly connects to the popularity data source, making this Integration rather than just Unit. Test 8 is clearly System-level since testing a 200ms response time constraint across 100k products requires actual infrastructure — a fast local machine won't reveal the real bottlenecks. I'm confident in these assessments now and ready to document them properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10039,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10039},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ef088771-b028-4578-8f7c-6660ea7e4215","uuid":"e63aaf35-bffc-46c5-b5c6-fbb44e083caa"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ANnUioxF82yzsGvHZYXf3K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018L5YdNBzi4h7z5sUM4XEva","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Out-of-stock products are excluded from recommendation results regardless of relevance score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is entirely within the availability filter function — given a list of products with stock flags, it must exclude out-of-stock items. No module boundary is crossed. REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess. MOCK-HIDE: An in-process list of products with stock status fully exercises the filter. LLM-DEP: No ML inference involved. REJECTION: Integration rejected — the failure mode is a single filter predicate, not a handoff between modules.","test_description":"Construct an in-memory product list where items A (in-stock, low score) and B (out-of-stock, high score) exist. Pass the list through the availability filter. Assert item B is absent from the output regardless of its relevance score, and item A is present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The user preference filter correctly excludes product categories the user has explicitly blocked.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives in the preference filter function — given blocked categories from user settings and a product list, it must exclude matching products. REAL-INFRA: User settings and catalog can both be in-process data structures. MOCK-HIDE: A real user settings object (or stub) with a known blocked list fully exercises the logic. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION: Integration rejected — there is no inter-module state handoff required to expose the failure; the filter logic is self-contained.","test_description":"Create a user settings object with blocked categories ['electronics', 'toys']. Build a product catalog containing items from 'electronics', 'toys', and 'clothing'. Run the preference filter. Assert no products from 'electronics' or 'toys' appear in the output, and 'clothing' products are retained.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The recommendation algorithm ranks products matching the user's recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the scoring/ranking function's weighting logic — a product in a recently browsed category must score higher than one with no browsing overlap. This is a deterministic algorithmic property testable with controlled inputs. REAL-INFRA: No external I/O needed. LLM-DEP: The algorithm is described as rule-based weighting of signals, not LLM inference — the expected output is deterministic given known inputs. REJECTION: Agentic rejected — no non-deterministic model inference is required to test that browsing signal raises rank.","test_description":"Provide the ranking algorithm with a fixed user browsing history (category 'shoes', 3 views) and two candidate products: P1 in category 'shoes' and P2 in category 'garden'. Invoke the ranker and assert P1 receives a strictly higher rank position than P2.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.55,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.11,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns the correct page of results with stable ordering — requesting page 2 twice returns identical results if underlying data is unchanged.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the pagination function's slice logic and the sort stability of the ranking step. Both can be exercised with a fixed in-memory ranked list. REAL-INFRA: No filesystem, network, or subprocess. MOCK-HIDE: A deterministic in-memory list fully exposes any instability or off-by-one in page slicing. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION: Integration rejected — stable sort and correct page slicing are pure algorithmic properties; no cross-module state is required.","test_description":"Build a fixed ranked list of 25 products. Call the paginator with page_size=10, page=2 twice consecutively on the same input. Assert both calls return the same 10 product IDs in the same order, and that the IDs are exactly positions 11–20 of the original ranked list.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The recommendation algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category the user hasn't browsed before (serendipity requirement).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The serendipity logic is a property of the ranker or post-processing step — it must inject diversity by including at least one unexplored category. With controlled input (known browsed categories, catalog covering additional categories), this is fully testable. REAL-INFRA: No external I/O. LLM-DEP: The serendipity rule is a deterministic constraint, not an ML inference quality judgment. REJECTION: Agentic rejected — the test checks presence of a rule outcome, not quality of an ML ranking; the pass/fail criterion is binary and deterministic.","test_description":"Set user browsing history to categories ['A', 'B', 'C']. Provide a catalog containing products in categories A, B, C, D, and E. Run the recommendation algorithm. Assert that the output list contains at least one product whose category is not in ['A', 'B', 'C'].","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.62,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A new user with no purchase or browsing history receives popularity-based recommendations rather than an empty result set.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The cold-start failure — returning an empty list instead of popularity fallback — only appears when the recommendation service is wired to the popularity data source. If the popularity store returns an empty stub, the bug (no fallback wiring) is hidden. The failure mode is at the boundary between the recommendation orchestrator and the popularity ranking module/store. REAL-INFRA: A real popularity data source is not required; a local fake DB or in-process stub popularity repository is sufficient. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION: Unit rejected — a unit test mocking the popularity source would pass even if the real wiring never calls the fallback path.","test_description":"Seed a local fake popularity store with product ranking data. Create a new user with empty purchase and browsing history. Call the recommendation service end-to-end. Assert the response is non-empty and that the returned products match the top-ranked items from the popularity store, not an empty list or error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records the correct product ID, position in the list, and timestamp for each recommendation the user interacts with.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure could be that the click event handler writes incorrect field values or fails to persist to the tracking store. This only surfaces when the handler is wired to the persistence layer. A Unit test mocking the store write would not catch serialization bugs, field mapping errors, or incorrect timestamp capture. REAL-INFRA: A real external service is not needed; a local in-memory or embedded tracking store suffices. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION: Unit rejected — mocking the store always passes even when the actual data written is wrong.","test_description":"Wire the click tracking handler to a local in-memory tracking store. Simulate a click on product ID 'P42' at list position 3 at a known timestamp T. After the event, query the tracking store. Assert exactly one record exists with product_id='P42', position=3, and timestamp within 1 second of T.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The response time for generating recommendations stays under 200ms for a catalog of 100,000 products.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Wall-clock latency at scale depends on real execution characteristics — DB query plans, network round trips, index behavior, and process overhead — that in-process fakes cannot replicate. An in-memory mock catalog of 100k items would give misleadingly fast results hiding real bottlenecks in serialization, DB scanning, or inter-service calls. MOCK-HIDE: Any mocked data layer will always satisfy 200ms trivially, hiding the real failure. REJECTION: Integration rejected — performance assertions at this scale require the real execution stack; no in-process wiring test can falsify the 200ms bound meaningfully.","test_description":"Deploy the recommendation service against a real (or realistic) catalog store pre-loaded with 100,000 products. Issue a recommendation request for a user with typical browsing history. Measure wall-clock end-to-end response time using a real HTTP client. Assert the response is received within 200ms. Run at least 10 trials and assert the p95 latency is under 200ms.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"When a recommended product is purchased, the recommendation algorithm deprioritizes it in subsequent requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure — purchased product still ranking highly — only appears when the recommendation orchestrator reads the purchase history store and the ranker applies the deprioritization rule across separate calls. A Unit test of just the ranker with injected purchase history would not catch a bug where the purchase event is never persisted or never read back. REAL-INFRA: A local fake purchase history store suffices; no real external service required. LLM-DEP: The deprioritization rule is deterministic. REJECTION: Unit rejected — the cross-call state dependency (write purchase, then read in next recommendation request) requires module wiring, not just isolated function logic.","test_description":"Using a local fake purchase store and recommendation service wired together: first request recommendations for user U and record product P's initial rank. Then record a purchase event for product P by user U into the fake store. Request recommendations again. Assert product P's rank is strictly lower than its initial rank, or that it is absent from the top-N results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Recommendation results are deterministic for the same user state — requesting recommendations twice with no intervening user activity returns the same ranked list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Determinism across two calls requires that the state-reading layer (purchase history, browsing log, catalog) is consistently queried. If any module introduces randomness or non-deterministic ordering, it only surfaces when two real calls read from the same underlying state. A Unit test of the ranker alone with the same injected input trivially returns the same output. REAL-INFRA: No external process needed; an in-process fake store is sufficient. LLM-DEP: The algorithm is described as deterministic weighting, not LLM inference; if it were LLM-based, the level would be Agentic. REJECTION: Agentic rejected — no non-deterministic model call is described; the determinism requirement applies to the pipeline's data access and ranking logic.","test_description":"Seed a local fake store with a fixed user state (known browsing history, purchase history, catalog). Call the recommendation service twice with the same user ID and no writes between calls. Assert the two response lists are identical in product IDs and in rank order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10039,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10039},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ef088771-b028-4578-8f7c-6660ea7e4215","uuid":"9fad37cf-515d-4955-a637-88b508231480"}
